<br><br>
Hope you men don't mind if I try to answer Teacher Guy's rhetorical question &quot;How can an average Grunt just shoot a woman.&quot; <br><br>
In America lack of understanding or unwillingness to accept what happens in times of war is part of the reasons for cries of woman and baby killer. The key to know how that might happen is found in the fact that they were not in the United States with its social mores and culture.  What is hard to understand in light of how women were respected and protected in the 60's, a peacetime economy within the Continental United States is totally different in war.  If one is to survive they cannot look at the person as a man, a woman, or a child. You either see an ally or an enemy. In war you capture or kill enemies before they kill you. <br><br>
If you are responsible for the perimeter and you see a Vietnamese woman who you spoke with on the compound during the daytime approach the wire, pull out cutters and crawl through the fence, you know that person is an enemy and up to no good.  To not respond is to risk the lives of your buddies.  If you are out on patrol and a small child wrapped with explosives heads toward you.  You yell to keep her away but she keeps toddling toward you, do you stop her or do you wait until she is in the midst of your men and one of the enemy blows her up themselves to get at you.  Either way the child is dead, but if you fire at least your buddies are still alive.  No one says that firing on another human being is an easy thing to do.  Some hesitate in the heat of battle and are killed.  Others fire in the heat of battle and have nightmares of the accusatory eyes of the enemy who lost.<br><br>

